definition: the final years of the Ch'ing or Qing dynasty/China at the turn of the 20th century
Ch'ing or Qing dynasty (1644-1911)
the late Qing and early Republic, i.e. China around 1911

the not-very-distant past/modern times, excluding recent decades/(in the context of Chinese history) the period from the Opium Wars until the May 4th Movement (mid-19th century to 1919)/capitalist times (pre-1949)
Li Hung-chang or Li Hongzhang (1823-1901), Qing dynasty general, politician and diplomat
the foreign learning or Westernizing faction in the late Qing
Republic of China (1912-1949)/used in Taiwan as the name of the calendar era (e.g. 民國六十年|民国六十年 is 1971, the 60th year after 1911)
late Ming/first half of the 17th century
Manchurian Qing (refers to the Qing dynasty, esp. at its decline, or as an anti-Qing slogan)

Hundred Days Reform (1898), failed attempt to reform the Qing dynasty
the Ch'ing or Qing dynasty (1644-1911)
